1
0:00:40,920 --> 0:00:43,420
一只丽龟
An olive ridley turtle.

2
0:00:46,260 --> 0:00:51,240
正在哥斯达黎加的浅水区休息
She's resting in the shallows off Costa Rica,

3
0:00:52,920 --> 0:00:56,720
为了到这儿 它已经游了上千英里
having swum a thousand miles to be here.

4
0:01:06,280 --> 0:01:12,240
只因为它的蛋必须孵在干燥的陆地上
All because the eggs she carries must be laid on dry land.

5
0:01:19,060 --> 0:01:22,600
现在 它又回到了十年前
Now she's returned to the very same beach

6
0:01:22,620 --> 0:01:25,200
那片曾经孵化她的沙滩上
where she hatched 10 years ago.

7
0:01:33,240 --> 0:01:38,340
它必须离开相对安全的海洋
She must leave the safety of her marine world

8
0:01:40,340 --> 0:01:44,120
勇敢去面对前方未知的世界
and brave the alien world beyond.

9
0:02:07,820 --> 0:02:09,820
虽然身怀六甲
She's heavily laden

10
0:02:09,860 --> 0:02:14,860
但它肩负着下一代的命运
but the future of the next generation of her kind is at stake.

11
0:02:22,100 --> 0:02:26,980
在沙滩沿岸 这一壮观的景象
All along the beach in a spectacle that has remained unchanged

12
0:02:27,020 --> 0:02:29,300
几百年来未曾改变
for millions or years,

13
0:02:29,340 --> 0:02:32,840
海龟妈妈们浮出海面
mother sea turtles emerge from the ocean

14
0:02:35,310 --> 0:02:38,040
成千上万
in their hundreds of thousands.

15
0:02:49,900 --> 0:02:53,580
只有那些能克服
Only those animals that overcome the great challenges

16
0:02:53,680 --> 0:02:55,760
海陆两地艰难险阻的动物
of both land and sea

17
0:02:56,000 --> 0:03:00,440
才能到达海岸 完成生命中最重要的使命
can make the most of life here on the coasts.

18
0:03:25,380 --> 0:03:30,820
海岸是个瞬息万变 馈赠丰厚的地方
Our shores are places of sudden changes and rich rewards.

19
0:03:34,980 --> 0:03:39,440
加拉帕戈斯群岛位于热带太平洋上
The Galapagos Islands in the tropical Pacific Ocean.

20
0:03:43,180 --> 0:03:46,560
这个荒芜的海岸看似并不宜居
Their barren coastline looks inhospitable,

21
0:03:46,600 --> 0:03:51,600
但有那么一群动物却能很好地适应
but one group of animals has learnt to use it to their advantage.

22
0:04:02,840 --> 0:04:04,940
海狮
Sea lions.

23
0:04:08,810 --> 0:04:10,140
单身汉们
Bachelors.

24
0:04:11,620 --> 0:04:14,320
他们需要快速增加体重
They need to pile on the pounds

25
0:04:14,360 --> 0:04:18,800
因为只有体格最大的雄海狮 才能吸引雌性与其交配
as only the biggest males will attract a female and manage to breed.

26
0:04:23,340 --> 0:04:27,460
如果这些年轻的海狮长得不够大
If these young bulls fail to grow big enough,

27
0:04:27,500 --> 0:04:31,760
他们就要在这偏僻的海岸线上继续流浪
they will remain exiled on this isolated shoreline.

28
0:04:39,160 --> 0:04:43,340
一只饥肠辘辘的小海狮独自出发了
So one hungry young bull heads out alone.

29
0:05:13,470 --> 0:05:16,580
它开始寻找饕餮盛宴了
He's on the hunt for big game.

30
0:05:24,650 --> 0:05:26,650
一群黄鳍金枪鱼
Yellowfin tuna.

31
0:05:29,740 --> 0:05:32,160
每条黄鳍金枪鱼重达60公斤
Each weighing 60 kilos

32
0:05:34,480 --> 0:05:37,540
时速最快可达40英里(约64km/h)
with a top speed of 40 miles an hour.

33
0:05:40,840 --> 0:05:43,980
在外海 海狮几乎抓不到它们
He can't possibly catch one in the open sea,

34
0:05:45,950 --> 0:05:48,080
但是海狮有一个妙计
but he has a plan.

35
0:05:50,600 --> 0:05:54,460
不远处就是海湾的入口
Ahead lies the entrance to the cove.

36
0:05:57,160 --> 0:05:59,680
他引诱着黄鳍金枪鱼
He herds them towards it

37
0:06:06,360 --> 0:06:08,240
掉入他的陷阱
into his trap.

38
0:06:23,480 --> 0:06:27,060
试图把它们逼到死胡同
Driving them into a dead end.

39
0:06:31,520 --> 0:06:34,140
但黄鳍金枪鱼躲掉了
But they give him the slip.

40
0:06:41,580 --> 0:06:43,740
小海狮失败了
He's failed.

41
0:06:52,600 --> 0:06:55,800
不过天无绝人之路
But there might be another way.

42
0:07:14,320 --> 0:07:16,880
现在海狮成群结队出动
Now they head off as a team

43
0:07:19,760 --> 0:07:22,600
来围捕更多的金枪鱼
to round up more tuna,

44
0:07:26,920 --> 0:07:30,560
并把它们逼进海湾
driving them back into the cove.

45
0:07:43,520 --> 0:07:48,840
海狮将金枪鱼赶到了狭口处
The sea lions fan out channelling the tuna towards the bottleneck.

46
0:08:05,530 --> 0:08:08,430
金枪鱼又一次回到了死胡同
Once again the tuna hit the dead end.

47
0:08:09,200 --> 0:08:12,000
但是这一次 年轻的雄海狮
But this time, the young bull doubles back

48
0:08:12,020 --> 0:08:15,820
封锁了出口
to act as a blocker sealing off the exit.

49
0:08:40,840 --> 0:08:43,660
一旦有鱼群想逃跑
This time when the shoal tries to escape,

50
0:08:43,680 --> 0:08:48,020
海狮又会把它们逼进下一个死胡同
he blocks them and drives them back into the next blind alley.

51
0:09:01,180 --> 0:09:05,740
现在海狮可以把它们依次解决了
The gang can now pick them off one by one.

52
0:09:50,900 --> 0:09:53,100
这个聪明的围捕技术
This clever fishing technique,

53
0:09:53,120 --> 0:09:56,880
需要极强的战略眼光和通力合作
demanding foresight, planning and cooperation,

54
0:09:56,920 --> 0:10:01,440
也只有在加拉帕戈斯群岛才可以看到
has only every been seen here in the Galapagos.

55
0:10:03,400 --> 0:10:08,040
一条大金枪鱼能提供的蛋白质含量
Each massive fish provides them with five times more protein

56
0:10:08,080 --> 0:10:09,880
就是平日捕猎一天所汲取的五倍
than a normal day's hunting.

57
0:10:14,860 --> 0:10:18,180
最后 这只年轻的海狮离开了他的岗位
Finally, the young bull leaves his post

58
0:10:21,180 --> 0:10:23,070
开始享用它的战利品
to claim his reward.

59
0:10:38,010 --> 0:10:40,440
以这些蛋白质丰富的金枪鱼为食
On a diet of protein-rich tuna,

60
0:10:41,180 --> 0:10:45,940
这只小海狮很快就会成长为强壮的雄性海狮
he's well on the way to becoming a full-sized breeding bull.

61
0:10:52,780 --> 0:10:54,360
利用这个海湾
By using this cove,

62
0:10:54,380 --> 0:10:58,780
加拉帕戈斯群岛的海狮们
these Galapagos sea lions have made the most of the opportunities

63
0:10:58,880 --> 0:11:02,620
充分把握了这得天独厚的优势
that occur where the coast's two worlds meet.

64
0:11:11,900 --> 0:11:16,520
因为潮起潮落 海岸是所有海洋栖息地中
Coasts are the most swiftly changing of all ocean habitats

65
0:11:17,630 --> 0:11:20,140
最为变化多端的
because of the tides.

66
0:11:28,040 --> 0:11:33,160
潮汐是月球引力作用于大海产生的
Tides are created as the moon's gravity pulls at the sea.

67
0:11:43,160 --> 0:11:48,360
月球的公转带来了潮起潮落
As the moon circles our planet, the seas rise and fall.

68
0:11:49,980 --> 0:11:51,980
通常一天两次
Typically twice a day,

69
0:11:53,500 --> 0:11:58,360
造就了地球上最长久的动态景观
creating the most constantly dynamic landscapes on Earth.

70
0:12:08,160 --> 0:12:13,800
也只有这里的海洋生物 需要面对如此多变的生存环境
Nowhere else do sea-living creatures face such changeable conditions.

71
0:12:16,740 --> 0:12:21,820
它们每天都要冒着被太阳炙烤烘干的危险
With the daily risk of drying out and being scorched by the sun.

72
0:12:27,700 --> 0:12:30,700
岩岸在潮汐退去后
Where the tide retreats across a rocky shore,

73
0:12:30,720 --> 0:12:33,980
会留下一片临时乐土
it can leave behind a temporary oasis.

74
0:12:41,720 --> 0:12:43,460
潮水潭
A rock pool.

75
0:12:55,070 --> 0:12:57,820
这里看似宁静的一隅
Seemingly, it's a haven of calm.

76
0:12:59,240 --> 0:13:02,300
但好景不长
But not for long.

77
0:13:03,680 --> 0:13:08,720
将镜头放快便可以看到意想不到的场景
Turning minutes into seconds reveals unexpected dramas.

78
0:13:21,580 --> 0:13:26,200
潮水潭里的食草动物 食腐动物和滤食性动物
In rock pools, grazers, scavengers and filter feeders

79
0:13:26,220 --> 0:13:29,020
必须在涨潮前
must all make the most of the few short hours

80
0:13:29,040 --> 0:13:30,940
充分利用这数个小时
before the tide returns.

81
0:13:47,780 --> 0:13:51,540
海葵吞下了触手可及的一切东西
Anemones gulp down anything they can reach.

82
0:13:52,960 --> 0:13:57,060
尽管有些时候这些东西很难消化
Though some meals are harder to digest than others.

83
0:14:05,320 --> 0:14:10,980
这个魔法世界很快就变成了战场
These magical worlds soon become battlegrounds.

84
0:14:13,980 --> 0:14:19,450
这个致命的猎食者 它有五只触手 加之底部的一张嘴
A deadly predator with five arms and on the underside a mouth.

85
0:14:23,180 --> 0:14:25,180
赭色海星
The ochre starfish.

86
0:14:29,580 --> 0:14:32,760
它正在寻找帽贝
And it's in search of limpets.

87
0:14:51,140 --> 0:14:53,850
对于有的帽贝而言 它们无处可逃
For some, there is no escape.

88
0:14:54,080 --> 0:14:55,850
海星吞噬了它们
It engulfed them.

89
0:15:03,860 --> 0:15:07,300
但是有的帽贝有秘密的防御武器
But other limpets have a secret defense.

90
0:15:09,580 --> 0:15:13,220
它们将套膜外翻作为防御盾
They deploy a slippery shield

91
0:15:14,960 --> 0:15:18,960
使海星失去立足点继而逃脱
which allows them to slide to safety.

92
0:15:22,820 --> 0:15:27,400
这只帽贝有一个私人保镖
And this limpet has its own personal bodyguard.

93
0:15:36,000 --> 0:15:39,460
一只咬合力极强的海鳞虫
A scale worm with a nasty nip.

94
0:15:44,180 --> 0:15:49,720
这只海星还是喜欢吃些不咬人的食物
The starfish prefers food that doesn't bite back.

95
0:15:50,500 --> 0:15:52,060
帽贝继续前行
The limpet carries on,

96
0:15:52,180 --> 0:15:56,140
它的保镖在其壳下得到庇护
its bodyguard tucked safe under its shell.

97
0:15:59,020 --> 0:16:00,740
但是有一种生物
But there is one creature

98
0:16:00,760 --> 0:16:04,460
让帽贝束手无策
that limpets have no defense against.

99
0:16:06,300 --> 0:16:08,840
那就是喉盘鱼
A clingfish.

100
0:16:10,300 --> 0:16:14,280
它的牙可以撬动帽贝的壳
It has teeth that can lever under the shell

101
0:16:15,220 --> 0:16:18,720
像拧瓶盖一样旋下帽贝
and twist the limpet off like a bottle top.

102
0:16:23,000 --> 0:16:25,460
喉盘鱼吞下了它
The clingfish then swallows it

103
0:16:25,480 --> 0:16:27,520
连壳一起
shell and all.

104
0:16:35,240 --> 0:16:40,240
这样的戏码在潮水潭里仅能上演数个小时
Rock pool dramas like these last just a few short hours

105
0:16:40,280 --> 0:16:43,000
随后潮水便会涨起
before the tide returns.

106
0:16:45,720 --> 0:16:52,360
大海每天潮起潮落
Every day the sea becomes land and the land becomes sea.

107
0:16:58,700 --> 0:17:01,520
带来新的机遇
Bringing new opportunities.

108
0:17:05,500 --> 0:17:07,780
莎莉飞毛腿蟹
A Sally Lightfoot crab,

109
0:17:10,640 --> 0:17:13,070
作为成百上千食草蟹中的一种 
one of thousands of shore crabs

110
0:17:13,100 --> 0:17:16,090
它们正等待着属于自己的时刻
just waiting for their moment.

111
0:17:17,860 --> 0:17:22,560
它们每天都聚集在巴西的热带海岸上
Every day they gather on the tropical shores of Brazil,

112
0:17:25,140 --> 0:17:28,440
等待退潮的那一刻
waiting for the tide to go out.

113
0:17:36,330 --> 0:17:39,400
将它们的觅食地展现出来
Which exposes their feeding ground,

114
0:17:40,200 --> 0:17:44,170
覆盖着海藻的岩石 离岸边一百多米远
seaweed covered rocks, a hundred metres from the shore.

115
0:17:53,360 --> 0:17:57,480
到达那里是一场与潮汐的赛跑
Getting there is a race against the tide.

116
0:18:03,660 --> 0:18:06,880
它们从一块石头跳到另一块石头上
They leap from rock to rock.

117
0:18:19,800 --> 0:18:23,840
这些螃蟹似乎很怕水
These crabs seem to be afraid of the water.

118
0:18:35,360 --> 0:18:37,710
这也事出有因
And for good reason.

119
0:18:50,020 --> 0:18:52,420
海鳝
The Moray eel.

120
0:18:54,120 --> 0:18:58,190
链蛇鳝是捕蟹专家
The chain Moray is a specialist crab hunter.

121
0:19:03,340 --> 0:19:09,020
它的钝齿可以轻易地抓住并压碎螃蟹的壳
It's blunt teeth can easily grip and crush a crab's shell.

122
0:19:12,840 --> 0:19:16,120
它是螃蟹最致命的敌人
It's the crab's deadliest enemy.

123
0:19:27,220 --> 0:19:31,320
但距离觅食地螃蟹还有很长的路要走
But the crab's feeding grounds are still a long way off.

124
0:19:36,860 --> 0:19:38,900
它们必须坚持下去
They must press on.

125
0:20:01,630 --> 0:20:03,040
路程已半
Halfway.

126
0:20:08,400 --> 0:20:11,520
但它们的天敌别有妙招
But their enemy has other ideas.

127
0:20:16,400 --> 0:20:18,540
穿过陆地
Crossing the land

128
0:20:24,300 --> 0:20:27,600
重设伏击
to reset the ambush.

129
0:20:29,900 --> 0:20:33,900
为了觅食 这些螃蟹不得不继续前行
To feed, the crabs must keep going.

130
0:20:40,240 --> 0:20:42,330
但是危险无处不在
But nowhere is safe.

131
0:20:46,320 --> 0:20:49,790
章鱼也是螃蟹的天敌
An octopus. Also a crab killer.

132
0:21:15,040 --> 0:21:17,860
螃蟹勇往直前
The crabs make a dash for it.

133
0:21:43,690 --> 0:21:44,830
它成功脱逃了
Made it.

134
0:21:53,960 --> 0:21:56,020
冒着生命危险
Risking life and limb

135
0:21:56,040 --> 0:21:59,020
终于吃到了海藻
to graze on these seaweed pastures.

136
0:22:02,480 --> 0:22:06,920
但两个小时后又要涨潮了
But in two hours' time when the tide starts to turn,

137
0:22:07,560 --> 0:22:11,080
它们不得不再次面对严酷挑战
they will have to run the gauntlet all over again.

138
0:22:20,440 --> 0:22:24,880
潮汐并不是冲击海岸的唯一力量
Tides are not the only force to have an impact on the coasts.

139
0:22:44,460 --> 0:22:48,200
来自远海的惊涛骇浪
The greatest waves originate far out to sea

140
0:22:48,220 --> 0:22:52,680
滚滚而来 咆哮着涌向海岸
and roll in towards the coast, growing as they come.

141
0:23:04,520 --> 0:23:08,900
在浅海海床的抬升下
As the shallowing sea floor drags at their underside,

142
0:23:08,940 --> 0:23:13,120
波峰可以上升到一百英尺高(约30.5米)
their crests rise up to a hundred feet high,

143
0:23:13,160 --> 0:23:16,400
巨浪倾覆进而平息
topple over and break.

144
0:23:22,480 --> 0:23:26,140
葡萄牙的扎雷所属海域 曾诞生了
Many of the biggest surfed waves in the world

145
0:23:26,180 --> 0:23:28,980
许多被冲浪选手征服过的世界级大浪
are formed off Nazare in Portugal.

146
0:23:44,330 --> 0:23:49,060
纳扎雷海岸每天的海浪冲击力
Every day along this coast, the impact of the waves is equivalent

147
0:23:49,120 --> 0:23:53,050
都相当于150万吨TNT炸药爆炸
to one and a half million tonnes of TNT.

148
0:24:14,460 --> 0:24:19,840
也正是浪潮的冲击渐渐塑造了我们的海岸
Wave power gradually moulds and reshapes our coasts.

149
0:24:23,300 --> 0:24:25,000
在欧洲的一些地方
In some parts of Europe,

150
0:24:25,020 --> 0:24:30,140
海浪每年冲蚀的海岸线长达3米
waves wear away as much as three metres of coastline each year.

151
0:24:37,180 --> 0:24:40,360
海浪重塑岩石的速率
The rate at which the waves reshape the rock

152
0:24:40,400 --> 0:24:42,580
取决于岩石自身的硬度
depends on its hardness.

153
0:24:43,870 --> 0:24:46,520
当软岩分布在硬岩下方时
Where soft rock lies below hard,

154
0:24:46,720 --> 0:24:48,840
就会形成奇特的拱形石
dramatic arches are craved.

155
0:25:06,160 --> 0:25:08,160
在西班牙北海岸
It's an endless assault

156
0:25:08,240 --> 0:25:12,160
海浪永不停歇的拍打敲击
that gradually sculpts vaulted cathedrals of stone

157
0:25:12,240 --> 0:25:14,480
逐渐雕刻出一个个拱形的石头教堂
as here in northern Spain.

158
0:25:26,040 --> 0:25:29,640
这些位于北极的悬崖峭壁
And wave power creates towering fortresses

159
0:25:29,760 --> 0:25:31,800
正是海浪为数万只海鸟
like these cliffs in these Arctic,

160
0:25:31,880 --> 0:25:35,560
打造的天然栖息堡垒
home to tens of thousands of breeding seabirds.

161
0:25:40,120 --> 0:25:44,240
悬崖的正面只能从空中到达
The faces of the cliffs are accessible only from the air

162
0:25:44,360 --> 0:25:48,160
其中有充足的角落和缝隙 供抵达的生物落脚
and have plenty of nooks and crannies for those that can get there.

163
0:25:53,240 --> 0:25:58,000
但为了觅食 海鸟还必须要掌控海洋的世界
But to feed, seabirds must still master the ocean world beyond.

164
0:26:03,160 --> 0:26:04,240
北极海鹦
The puffin.

165
0:26:08,160 --> 0:26:09,600
他是名渔夫
He's a fisherman...

166
0:26:11,040 --> 0:26:12,400
也是个父亲
...and a father.

167
0:26:16,680 --> 0:26:19,000
这是他的伴侣
He has a mate for life.

168
0:26:25,960 --> 0:26:30,000
它们共同担负起养育小海鹦的重任
Both share the burden of raising their week-old chick,

169
0:26:30,080 --> 0:26:34,120
一周大的小海鹦 每天需要投喂五次
their puffling who needs five square meals a day.

170
0:26:36,760 --> 0:26:39,720
它的父母轮流出海捕鱼
The parents alternate fishing trips.

171
0:26:43,040 --> 0:26:44,680
现在轮到爸爸了
It's dad's turn.

172
0:27:07,200 --> 0:27:09,440
当鱼类数量较少时
When fish stocks are low,

173
0:27:09,520 --> 0:27:13,560
海鹦必须出海飞行30多英里(约48km)
puffins must fly as much as 30 miles out sea

174
0:27:14,800 --> 0:27:17,400
才能到达渔场
to reach the good fishing grounds.

175
0:27:29,400 --> 0:27:33,360
随后便潜入另一片新天地
Once there,they plunge into another world.

176
0:27:41,720 --> 0:27:45,680
良好的捕鱼点很难占据 并且它们有竞争对手
Good fishing spots are hard to come by, and they have company.

177
0:27:47,640 --> 0:27:48,960
海鸠
Guillemots.

178
0:27:56,280 --> 0:28:00,080
跟海鹦一样 它们的翅膀很短 适合潜水
Like the puffin, their wings are short and good for diving.

179
0:28:02,960 --> 0:28:05,920
海鹦能屏息超过一分钟
Puffins can hold their breath for over a minute

180
0:28:06,120 --> 0:28:09,080
并能潜入40米深的水域
and dive as deep as 40 metres.

181
0:28:14,320 --> 0:28:15,720
抓到一条
A catch.

182
0:28:34,720 --> 0:28:37,560
但归途漫漫
But it's a long way home.

183
0:28:50,880 --> 0:28:55,360
在飞越长达60英里(约97km)的艰辛路途后
After an exhausting round trip of almost 60 miles,

184
0:28:55,520 --> 0:28:57,680
这只海鹦就快要成功了
this puffin's nearly made it.

185
0:28:59,960 --> 0:29:02,320
但海岸线还有海盗虎视眈眈
But there are pirates on this coast.

186
0:29:05,840 --> 0:29:07,520
北极贼欧
Arctic Skuas.

187
0:29:32,520 --> 0:29:36,040
所有回家的父母都会遭受抢劫
All around returning parents are being robbed.

188
0:30:02,160 --> 0:30:05,080
贼欧因有长且向后倾斜的翅膀
The skuas' long rake back wings

189
0:30:05,160 --> 0:30:07,400
飞行更为迅速敏捷
make them faster and more manoeuvrable.

190
0:30:45,760 --> 0:30:48,640
海鹦们必须得明智地把握时机
Puffins must choose their moment wisely.

191
0:31:09,160 --> 0:31:11,130
一次惊险的逃脱
A near miss.

192
0:31:28,120 --> 0:31:31,120
拼尽全力进行最后冲刺
A last desperate burst of speed,

193
0:31:33,600 --> 0:31:35,040
它成功了
and it's made it.

194
0:32:01,400 --> 0:32:05,360
历经三小时的往返
Safely home after a three-hour round trip...

195
0:32:12,720 --> 0:32:15,320
在伴侣耐心的等待中 平安到家
...where his patient partner is waiting.

196
0:32:31,640 --> 0:32:34,600
今天小海鹦将饱餐一顿
Today their puffling will eat.

197
0:32:41,320 --> 0:32:44,080
但在鱼类资源衰减的地区
But where fish numbers are in decline,

198
0:32:44,200 --> 0:32:48,480
许多海鹦很难为雏鸟捕获充足的食物
many puffins now find it hard to get enough food for their chicks.

199
0:32:51,040 --> 0:32:53,080
在海洋生态每况愈下的今天
In the changing seas of today,

200
0:32:53,200 --> 0:32:57,080
想做成功的海鹦父母更加艰难
it can be even harder to be a successful puffin parent.

201
0:33:07,880 --> 0:33:12,000
同时接受两种空间的挑战很不容易
Overcoming the challenges of two worlds is seldom easy.

202
0:33:14,040 --> 0:33:18,600
有一种海洋生物几乎完全脱离了海洋
One marine creature has virtually abandoned the sea altogether.

203
0:33:21,560 --> 0:33:24,240
在几个偏远的太平洋岛屿上
On a few remote pacific islands,

204
0:33:24,320 --> 0:33:27,800
生活着地球上最爱在陆地生活的鱼
lives the most terrestrial fish on the planet.

205
0:33:33,720 --> 0:33:37,160
在这个数米高石灰岩悬崖的顶端
At the top of this metre-high limestone cliff,

206
0:33:40,920 --> 0:33:45,360
一只八厘米长的岩跳鱼已经拥有了一个巢穴
an eight-centimetre long blenny has chosen a nest hole.

207
0:33:51,800 --> 0:33:55,160
在这里 他可以安心在充足的海藻上生活
Up here, he can graze on the abundant algae

208
0:33:55,280 --> 0:33:58,320
没有任何海水鱼类与它竞争
without any competition from sea-going fish.

209
0:34:00,120 --> 0:34:02,360
一群雌性岩跳鱼在他下方觅食
The females are feeding beneath him.

210
0:34:06,640 --> 0:34:09,040
他渴望引起她们的注意
He's keen to attract their attention,

211
0:34:11,880 --> 0:34:14,800
但她们正忙着保湿
but they are busy moisturising.

212
0:34:15,240 --> 0:34:19,120
保持湿润非常重要 因为它们通过皮肤呼吸
Staying damp is essential as they breathe through their skin.

213
0:34:24,120 --> 0:34:28,440
为了使自己更具吸引力 他变成了黑色
To make himself conspicuous,he turns black

214
0:34:32,680 --> 0:34:35,240
并不断抖动橙色的鳍
and flashes his orange fin.

215
0:34:37,080 --> 0:34:38,640
他终于吸引了她的眼球
He catches her eye.

216
0:34:41,440 --> 0:34:44,240
但这些太平洋跳跃好手
But these Pacific leaping blennies,

217
0:34:44,360 --> 0:34:47,000
似乎很害怕海浪
seem afraid of the waves.

218
0:34:50,360 --> 0:34:52,280
它们不擅长游泳
They're poor swimmers

219
0:34:53,120 --> 0:34:55,400
并很容易在海中被捕食
and will be easy prey in the sea.

220
0:34:58,120 --> 0:35:00,280
再试一次
Time to try again.

221
0:35:03,880 --> 0:35:05,080
她心动了
She's tempted.

222
0:35:10,040 --> 0:35:13,680
但海浪再次扫了兴
But once again distracted by a wave.

223
0:35:37,200 --> 0:35:39,680
雄性岩跳鱼没有放弃
The male just won't give up.

224
0:35:52,040 --> 0:35:53,800
最终 她着迷了
Finally, she's hooked.

225
0:35:58,280 --> 0:35:59,800
他把路让开
He makes way...

226
0:36:02,400 --> 0:36:05,160
让她能顺利进入他的巢穴
so she can enter his cave.

227
0:36:09,200 --> 0:36:12,040
并用他诱人的舞蹈
And he encourages her to lay her eggs

228
0:36:12,120 --> 0:36:14,760
鼓励她在此产卵
with his seductive dance.

229
0:36:29,040 --> 0:36:33,320
然后 他在安全的巢穴中给这些卵受精
He then fertilizes them in the safety of his nest.

230
0:36:43,800 --> 0:36:47,840
岩跳鱼为了陆地上的生活放弃了海洋
The blenny has given up the sea for a life on land.

231
0:36:50,160 --> 0:36:54,040
有种生物在另一领域内
Others have made an even more successful move

232
0:36:54,120 --> 0:36:56,480
有了更成功的实践
but in a different direction.

233
0:37:03,720 --> 0:37:06,280
企鹅放弃了飞行
Penguins have abandoned flying

234
0:37:06,360 --> 0:37:09,800
并用大半生的时间来游泳
and instead spend most of their lives swimming.

235
0:37:11,600 --> 0:37:14,880
它们的羽毛像光滑的救生衣
Their sleek survival suits of tightly packed feathers

236
0:37:14,960 --> 0:37:17,560
非常适合在冰冷的水域遨游
are perfect for these freezing waters.

237
0:37:19,480 --> 0:37:22,440
但是它们一年还是要上岸一次
Yet, they must still come ashore once a year.

238
0:37:36,480 --> 0:37:41,320
这里是靠近南极洲的南乔治亚岛
South Georgia, an island wilderness close to Antarctica.

239
0:37:51,840 --> 0:37:55,680
每年春天 成千上万的王企鹅回到这里
Each spring, its beaches become the busiest on Earth

240
0:37:55,760 --> 0:37:59,600
使这片海滩成为地球上最繁忙的地方
as hundreds of thousands of king penguins return here.

241
0:38:09,400 --> 0:38:11,200
他们正在前往聚集地
They're heading for the colony.

242
0:38:18,240 --> 0:38:22,760
但他们要穿过这世界上最大的肉体墙壁
But in their way lies the biggest wall of blubber on the planet.

243
0:38:27,040 --> 0:38:28,920
象海豹
Elephant seals.

244
0:38:36,640 --> 0:38:38,640
现在正是繁殖的季节
It's the breeding season

245
0:38:38,800 --> 0:38:43,560
重达四吨的"公牛"们 正为他们的女眷相互搏斗
and the four-tonne bulls are fighting for control of their harems.

246
0:38:46,680 --> 0:38:49,240
最好等待他们冷静下来
Best to wait for them to calm down.

247
0:39:04,120 --> 0:39:06,440
他不能从这障碍上飞过去
He can't fly over this barrier,

248
0:39:06,520 --> 0:39:10,440
只能尽量轻声漫步 降低自己的存在感
so he will have to walk as unobtrusively as possible.

249
0:39:14,000 --> 0:39:18,280
并希望沉睡的巨人不要醒来
And hope that sleeping giants will continue to lie.

250
0:39:30,880 --> 0:39:32,530
小心
Careful.

251
0:39:49,520 --> 0:39:51,850
麻烦来了
This could be tricky.

252
0:40:08,960 --> 0:40:11,520
一头雄性象海豹被对手挑衅
A rival bull mounts a challenge.

253
0:40:13,600 --> 0:40:16,600
企鹅可能会被卷入这场交火中
The penguins could be caught in the crossfire.

254
0:40:47,720 --> 0:40:50,320
八吨脂肪相撞
Eight tonnes of blubber collide.

255
0:41:11,440 --> 0:41:15,000
这只高大的搏击大师取得胜利
The towering beach master is victorious.

256
0:41:22,040 --> 0:41:25,400
这只企鹅在疑惑中悄悄溜走
In the confusion,this penguin slips through.

257
0:41:28,360 --> 0:41:31,760
前面有4万只小企鹅
Ahead are 40,000 chicks.

258
0:41:35,520 --> 0:41:37,720
饥饿并兴奋着
Hungry and over-excited.

259
0:41:53,320 --> 0:41:56,400
但并不是每只企鹅都有孩子要喂
But not every penguin has a chick to feed.

260
0:41:56,800 --> 0:41:58,720
他们并非为此而来
That's not why they're here.

261
0:42:02,760 --> 0:42:04,640
而是另有目的
There is another reason.

262
0:42:06,520 --> 0:42:10,960
每个企鹅都要面临一场对耐力的考验
There is a trial of endurance that every penguin must face,

263
0:42:12,640 --> 0:42:16,080
这个考验的开始 就是持续的瘙痒
and it starts with a persistent itch.

264
0:42:23,320 --> 0:42:25,840
他的救生服已经在
His survival suit has been worn thin

265
0:42:25,920 --> 0:42:28,840
为期数月的南大洋游泳中磨损
by months of swimming in the rough southern ocean.

266
0:42:31,360 --> 0:42:33,280
解决方案很粗暴
His solution is drastic.

267
0:42:37,200 --> 0:42:40,960
尽快把四层羽毛都蜕下来
Shed all four layers of feathers as quickly as possible.

268
0:42:46,000 --> 0:42:49,640
这个过程被称为毁坏式脱毛
The process is known as a catastrophic moult.

269
0:42:55,760 --> 0:42:58,000
在新的羽毛生出之前
Until their feathers regrow,

270
0:42:58,120 --> 0:43:01,560
企鹅要一直驻扎在此地
penguins will remain rooted to the spot.

271
0:43:24,280 --> 0:43:26,440
已经挨饿一个月了
Having starved for a month,

272
0:43:26,600 --> 0:43:30,920
它们现在不能碰水 再次与世隔绝
they're now fully waterproofed and insulated once more.

273
0:43:46,160 --> 0:43:51,640
饥饿使它们迫切回到海中的生活
Lean, hungry and eager to return to a life at sea.

274
0:44:08,360 --> 0:44:10,680
得力于它们防水的羽毛
Thanks to their waterproof plumage,

275
0:44:10,800 --> 0:44:13,840
企鹅能充分利用两种空间存活
penguins are able to make the most of both worlds

276
0:44:13,960 --> 0:44:17,160
即使在地球上最恶劣的环境下也是如此
even in some of the harshest conditions on Earth.

277
0:44:32,640 --> 0:44:34,200
南乔治亚岛的海岸
The coasts of South Georgia

278
0:44:34,280 --> 0:44:37,080
由于地处偏远 受到了保护
are currently protected by their remoteness.

279
0:44:39,640 --> 0:44:42,800
其他海岸线则脆弱的多
Other coastlines are much more vulnerable,

280
0:44:47,560 --> 0:44:51,200
现在它们的变化速度 比以往任何时候都快
and they are now changing faster than ever before.

281
0:44:55,760 --> 0:45:00,040
有三分之二的主要城市都位于海岸线上
Two thirds of our major cities are on our coasts.

282
0:45:02,800 --> 0:45:05,360
据估计 未来十年
It's estimated that in the next decade,

283
0:45:05,440 --> 0:45:09,960
全球剩余的原生态海岸中约有10%
we can expect 10% of the world's remaining wild shores

284
0:45:10,040 --> 0:45:13,000
将被人工开发
to be taken over by human development.

285
0:45:22,240 --> 0:45:25,320
然而每年 只要沿着佛罗里达的棕榈海滩走一走
Yet every year, just off Florida's Palm Beach

286
0:45:26,080 --> 0:45:30,040
就能发现许多无人留意的壮丽景象
and extraordinary spectacle appears almost unnoticed.

287
0:45:36,360 --> 0:45:40,640
那就是地球上最大的沿海鲨鱼种群
The biggest gathering of coastal sharks on the planet.

288
0:45:45,720 --> 0:45:48,400
短鳍真鲨和黑鳍鲨
Spinners and blacktips.

289
0:45:53,480 --> 0:45:55,080
足有一万头之多
Ten thousand of them.

290
0:46:05,400 --> 0:46:09,120
每年一月 它们寻找这些气候温暖的浅海
Every January, they seek out these warm shallows

291
0:46:09,560 --> 0:46:12,840
以便在北上迁移的途中作短暂停留
as a stopover on their migration northwards.

292
0:46:19,280 --> 0:46:24,000
鲨鱼们早在人类踏足这里之前 就开始在此地聚集了
Sharks have been gathering here since long before people arrived.

293
0:46:34,840 --> 0:46:38,040
但如今 它们面临着大量的污染
But today, they face levels of pollution

294
0:46:38,560 --> 0:46:42,520
栖息地的恶化以及海洋捕鱼的威胁
and habitat degradation as well as fishing pressures.

295
0:46:42,640 --> 0:46:46,320
而这些是它们祖先从未遭遇过的
that their ancestors would never have experienced.

296
0:46:50,000 --> 0:46:53,200
海岸生物主宰自己地盘的日子
It's not longer enough for coastal creatures

297
0:46:53,280 --> 0:46:55,600
已然一去不复返了
to master their own worlds.

298
0:47:03,800 --> 0:47:09,520
现如今又要面临来自我们人类世界的种种挑战
Now they must face the many challenges that come from our world, too.

299
0:47:09,520 --> 0:47:11,520


300
0:47:32,040 --> 0:47:34,840
为了拍摄最奇妙的沿海生物
To film the most surprising coastal wildlife,

301
0:47:34,960 --> 0:47:36,320
蓝色星球II的团队
the Blue Planet II team

302
0:47:36,400 --> 0:47:39,320
来到了地球上最偏远的几处海岸
travelled to some of the remotest shores on the planet.

303
0:47:42,480 --> 0:47:45,520
其中之一就是加拉帕戈斯群岛
One destination was the Galapagos islands.

304
0:47:47,080 --> 0:47:50,480
在这里 他们从当地摄影师理查德 乌勒克姆
Here they were in search of an almost unbelievable story

305
0:47:50,560 --> 0:47:53,560
口中挖掘出一个奇迹般的故事
brought to them by a local cameraman Richard Wollocombe.

306
0:47:55,480 --> 0:47:56,720
这件事还是我听我的一个
Well, I was talking to a friend of mine

307
0:47:56,720 --> 0:47:57,840
当地的渔夫朋友说的
who's a fisherman over here,

308
0:47:57,920 --> 0:48:01,820
他说某一次他来到这个海湾的时候
and he said that one day he turned up here in this bay,

309
0:48:02,010 --> 0:48:07,160
忽然看见一群海狮正在追捕金枪鱼群
and suddenly he saw a group of sea lions chasing these massive tuna

310
0:48:07,280 --> 0:48:09,040
直追到海滩上
up onto the beach.

311
0:48:09,400 --> 0:48:12,280
我当时想"编得真有意思 我才不信呢"
And I was like, "Yeah, funny one. I don't believe a word of that."

312
0:48:12,400 --> 0:48:14,160
那听起来太不可思议了
That just sounds too unreal.

313
0:48:14,560 --> 0:48:16,840
但是渔夫的故事太诱人了
Still the lure of the fisherman's tale

314
0:48:16,920 --> 0:48:18,760
以至于我们很难忽略它
was too great to ignore.

315
0:48:19,200 --> 0:48:21,800
我有点紧张 如果那不是真的话
I'm a little nervous that if it doesn't happen,

316
0:48:22,120 --> 0:48:23,360
我的名声可就不保了
there goes my credibility.

317
0:48:26,060 --> 0:48:29,840
蓝色星球II团队开始了地毯式的考察
The Blue Planet II team launch a full-scale expedition,

318
0:48:32,240 --> 0:48:34,720
但是一名成员仍将信将疑
but one of them is still skeptical.

319
0:48:35,200 --> 0:48:37,580
如果海狮真的会去捕猎金枪鱼的话
It's gonna be pretty spectacular if...

320
0:48:38,120 --> 0:48:41,120
那将是非常惊人的场景
if a sea lion could actually chase down and kill a tuna.

321
0:48:41,150 --> 0:48:43,400
总之我是不信
I'm still yet to be convinced.

322
0:48:44,840 --> 0:48:47,680
他们在这片荒芜的小海湾搭起了帐篷
They set up camp in this barren cove,

323
0:48:48,280 --> 0:48:51,040
作为接下来一个月的住所
home for the next month.

324
0:48:52,600 --> 0:48:55,520
当地的野生动物出了名的温顺
The local wildlife, famed for its tameness,

325
0:48:55,600 --> 0:48:57,920
它们对自己的新邻居充满好奇
is curious to meet its new neighbours.

326
0:49:09,160 --> 0:49:11,520
虽然尚未发现海狮的踪迹
With no sign of the sea lions,

327
0:49:11,600 --> 0:49:15,960
全体成员还是用远距离水下摄像机监视着这片海湾
the crew stake out the cove with remote underwater cameras.

328
0:49:18,760 --> 0:49:21,880
现场助理罗比 派普勒斯值第一轮班
Field assistant Roby Pepolas takes first watch.

329
0:49:23,240 --> 0:49:24,600
这里就是
This is the point of view

330
0:49:24,840 --> 0:49:26,880
我们用来观察海狮
where we try to see the sea lions come in

331
0:49:27,000 --> 0:49:28,680
从水中跳出来的地点
jumping over the water.

332
0:49:28,760 --> 0:49:31,080
如果海狮们距离非常近的话
If they're definitely coming very close,

333
0:49:31,160 --> 0:49:34,800
他们就会说"行动起来"或者"一起摇摆"
they say, "Action, action," or "Rock and roll."

334
0:49:38,480 --> 0:49:40,160
三小时后
Three hours later...

335
0:49:46,880 --> 0:49:48,840
航空摄像组是最先行动起来的
The aerial team are first up.

336
0:49:52,160 --> 0:49:55,000
这是一只海狮正把金枪鱼群赶进海湾
It's a sea lion chasing tuna into the bay.

337
0:50:10,160 --> 0:50:11,800
噢 它捕到了
Oh, he's got it. He's got it.

338
0:50:12,840 --> 0:50:14,160
难以置信
Unbelievable!

339
0:50:14,360 --> 0:50:16,240
看那儿 他还在挣扎
Look at that, he's still struggling.

340
0:50:16,520 --> 0:50:17,960
天哪
Holy moly!

341
0:50:20,320 --> 0:50:21,360
被挣脱了
He's lost him.

342
0:50:22,080 --> 0:50:24,520
金枪鱼溜走了
The tuna gives the sea lion the slip.

343
0:50:30,160 --> 0:50:33,600
接下来的几天里 更多海狮来到这片海湾
Over the coming days, more sea lions arrive in the cove

344
0:50:33,680 --> 0:50:35,680
捕猎黄鳍金枪鱼
chasing in yellowfin tuna.

345
0:50:38,780 --> 0:50:40,480
对 对 对
Yeah, yeah, yeah, ooh!

346
0:50:41,000 --> 0:50:43,360
我敢打赌肯定会有更多的金枪鱼和海狮过来
I bet you there's more tuna and another sea lion.

347
0:50:43,880 --> 0:50:46,320
那片小水洼里大概有六条金枪鱼
There's like six tuna in that bay.

348
0:50:56,040 --> 0:50:58,480
一头海狮引起了理查德的注意
One sea lion has caught Richard's attention,

349
0:50:58,560 --> 0:51:01,800
他亲切地称呼它为泰格博
and he's affectionately called him Tagboy.

350
0:51:02,800 --> 0:51:05,680
它与众不同 是个经验丰富的老猎手
He's really different. He's, like, a prolific hunter,

351
0:51:05,800 --> 0:51:07,600
并且格外灵巧
and he's really agile.

352
0:51:08,280 --> 0:51:13,120
有它出现的镜头都很精彩
It's just fascinating to watch and see the picture emerge about who he is.

353
0:51:14,640 --> 0:51:17,080
自空中俯瞰的无人机显示了
From above, the drone is revealing

354
0:51:17,160 --> 0:51:19,680
海狮是如何聚在一起捕猎的
how the group of sea lions are hunting together.

355
0:51:20,080 --> 0:51:22,080
从空中我们可以真切地看到海狮的进攻战略
From the air, we really see the strategy of the sea lion

356
0:51:22,160 --> 0:51:24,880
并且可以明显看出它们的分工
and see them with their individual roles as well.

357
0:51:25,000 --> 0:51:26,720
泰格博待在水渠中央
Tagboy stays off in the middle of the channel

358
0:51:26,800 --> 0:51:28,360
防止有金枪鱼逃脱
to make sure none of them escape.

359
0:51:28,440 --> 0:51:29,440
每只海狮都扮演自己的角色
Everyone's got a role

360
0:51:29,520 --> 0:51:31,640
它们形成了一个真正的团队
and they're really a team in bringing them together.

361
0:51:32,640 --> 0:51:35,680
尽管海狮们一直在浅水区捕猎
Although the sea lions have been hunting in the shallows,

362
0:51:35,760 --> 0:51:39,440
大家还是看到它们将一条金枪鱼驱赶到海滩上
the crew are yet to see them drive a tuna onto the beach.

363
0:51:42,080 --> 0:51:46,400
糟糕的是 海狮们并非这里唯一的狩猎者
And to make matters worse, the sea lions aren't alone in this cove.

364
0:51:53,360 --> 0:51:56,360
这里还有足足两米长的加拉帕戈斯鲨鱼
Galapagos sharks, each two metres long.

365
0:52:00,040 --> 0:52:02,320
这些鲨鱼几乎游到了海滩上
The shark almost beached itself

366
0:52:02,400 --> 0:52:05,320
并且从大海狮那里偷走了金枪鱼
and stole the tuna from the big sea lion,

367
0:52:06,040 --> 0:52:09,040
海狮懊恼不已
who is now really angry.

368
0:52:10,800 --> 0:52:12,120
尽管水中有鲨鱼
Despite the sharks,

369
0:52:12,240 --> 0:52:16,200
为了拍摄到整个画面 理查德必须进入海水中
to reveal the full story, Richard needs to get in the water.

370
0:52:17,120 --> 0:52:20,320
鲨鱼捕猎的惯用伎俩 靠海水中的血迹
Classic shark attack scenario. Blood in the water, shallow,

371
0:52:20,640 --> 0:52:22,520
他们很容易认错对象
and easy mistaken identity.

372
0:52:29,160 --> 0:52:30,720
当心你的手 罗比
Watch your hands, Roby.

373
0:52:31,360 --> 0:52:34,840
工作人员们穿了防护服以保护自己
The crew gain some protection from chain mail suits.

374
0:52:44,600 --> 0:52:45,840
简直是鲨鱼派对了
now a shark pool.

375
0:52:45,920 --> 0:52:48,720
一 二 三 四 五 现在有六条鲨鱼了
One, two, three, four, five, six sharks now.

376
0:52:49,960 --> 0:52:54,640
海水中大量的血让这些鲨鱼近乎疯狂
With so much blood in the water, the sharks go into a feeding frenzy.

377
0:53:08,800 --> 0:53:10,920
瞬间就把金枪鱼撕成了碎片
Make mince meat of these tuna in seconds.

378
0:53:11,040 --> 0:53:15,480
坦白讲 这么近距离地观察
To be so close to something so unbelievably ferocious

379
0:53:15,880 --> 0:53:18,080
如此凶残和危险的画面
and dangerous, quite frankly,

380
0:53:18,320 --> 0:53:20,200
真的很奇妙
is amazing. It's... It's...

381
0:53:20,560 --> 0:53:22,880
能躲在这后面真是太好了
It's nice to be able to hide behind all this though.

382
0:53:24,960 --> 0:53:28,200
然而 活跃了一个星期以后
But then, after a week of increasing activity,

383
0:53:28,280 --> 0:53:31,240
海狮忽然停止了捕猎
the sea lions suddenly stop fishing.

384
0:53:37,070 --> 0:53:38,170
自从我们开始观察以来
It's the first day though

385
0:53:38,170 --> 0:53:39,050
这是我们第一次
that we haven't seen any action

386
0:53:39,100 --> 0:53:42,360
一整天都没有看到任何海狮活动
during the whole day. Since we start.

387
0:53:43,160 --> 0:53:44,800
我们有点儿担心
We are kind of worried.

388
0:53:46,440 --> 0:53:48,400
金枪鱼消失了
The tuna have disappeared.

389
0:54:00,240 --> 0:54:01,680
理查德十分担忧
Richard is worried.

390
0:54:02,160 --> 0:54:04,800
种种迹象表明
The signs are starting to show

391
0:54:04,860 --> 0:54:08,920
随着海洋变暖 它们的活动越来越少
across the globe that the seas are warming, they're becoming less productive.

392
0:54:09,440 --> 0:54:13,560
加拉帕戈斯的海洋生物需要不断翻滚上涌的
Galapagos marine life relies on cold, deep currents

393
0:54:13,680 --> 0:54:17,200
上升寒流来不断补充水面的营养物质
welling up intermittently to fertilize the surface waters.

394
0:54:19,080 --> 0:54:21,560
如果海水上涌变得不那么频繁
If those upwellings become less consistent,

395
0:54:21,720 --> 0:54:24,080
这些生物将处于危险的境地
er, their lives could well be in jeopardy.

396
0:54:25,680 --> 0:54:26,720
过去
In the past,

397
0:54:26,800 --> 0:54:30,040
每当寒流上涌暂时停止的时候
when these cold water upwellings have temporarily stopped,

398
0:54:30,520 --> 0:54:32,800
大量海狮就会被饿死
many sea lions have starved to death.

399
0:54:33,960 --> 0:54:37,520
而温暖的海水更会削弱这些上升流
And a warming ocean could further weaken these upwellings.

400
0:54:43,080 --> 0:54:46,080
两个周的焦急等待过后
Then after two weeks of nervous waiting,

401
0:54:46,200 --> 0:54:47,480
出现了转机
a hopeful sign.

402
0:54:47,560 --> 0:54:50,560
一场大雾降临在这片海湾
A thick fog descends over the cove.

403
0:54:51,320 --> 0:54:54,080
开始有寒流翻滚 上涌
We've got very cold water that's come up, upwelled,

404
0:54:54,360 --> 0:54:55,840
并蔓延到整片海域
and spread across the ocean,

405
0:54:56,320 --> 0:54:58,440
这些冷水和温暖的空气相遇 产生了大雾
and mixed with the warm air, creating the fog

406
0:54:59,120 --> 0:55:00,960
我们希望这些冷水
and hoping that this cold water

407
0:55:01,480 --> 0:55:05,040
能缓解目前的困境 让海狮的捕猎重新开始
will just kick things off a bit, you know, and get the action going.

408
0:55:05,920 --> 0:55:08,680
当浓雾渐渐散去 振奋人心的场景出现了
As the fog clears, a welcome sight...

409
0:55:09,720 --> 0:55:13,440
金枪鱼群回到了这里 海狮们紧随其后
The tuna are back with sea lions hot on their heels.

410
0:55:16,720 --> 0:55:18,480
工作人员立刻行动起来
The crew leap into action.

411
0:55:27,440 --> 0:55:28,560
在水里
Being in the water,

412
0:55:28,640 --> 0:55:32,000
理查德可以跟拍海狮的团队行动
Richard can at last follow the sea lions' teamwork

413
0:55:36,640 --> 0:55:40,360
最终他拍到了泰格博将一条金枪鱼拖上岸的画面
and finally film Tagboy beaching a tuna.

414
0:55:42,080 --> 0:55:44,840
它们了解这迷宫一样的地形
The know the bottlenecks in this labyrinth.

415
0:55:45,200 --> 0:55:47,360
它们知道如何将猎物引入这些狭道之中
They know how to push them into those bottlenecks

416
0:55:47,480 --> 0:55:48,800
正是泰格博
and threre was just Tagboy,

417
0:55:48,880 --> 0:55:51,520
用它巨大的身躯封住了入口
almost his entire body was blocking the entrance,

418
0:55:51,720 --> 0:55:54,960
它只是优雅地来回游动 就让金枪鱼筋疲力尽
and he was just gently back and forth tiring the fish out.

419
0:55:55,560 --> 0:55:58,360
绝对令人惊叹 非常非常震撼人心
Absolutely extraordinary. Really, really impressive.

420
0:55:59,160 --> 0:56:00,240
蕾切尔导演
Director Rachel

421
0:56:00,320 --> 0:56:03,160
对海狮油然而生一股赞叹
has a newfound respect for the sea lions.

422
0:56:03,560 --> 0:56:05,800
我从不知道它们能够
I had no idea they were capable

423
0:56:05,880 --> 0:56:11,120
达到这种程度的组织和团队协作
of this level of planning and strategy and teamwork.

424
0:56:11,240 --> 0:56:13,720
我从不知道它们如此聪明
I had no idea they were this intelligent.

425
0:56:15,120 --> 0:56:19,520
理查德成功地拍摄到了这场独特的捕猎行动
Richard has succeeded in filming this unique hunting strategy

426
0:56:19,600 --> 0:56:23,640
这证明了渔夫所言非虚
and in doing so has proved the fisherman's tale to be true.

427
0:56:24,200 --> 0:56:28,080
海狮拥有让人难以置信的高智商
The sea lions' intelligence is unbelievably sophisticated.

428
0:56:28,640 --> 0:56:32,960
这远远超出了我的想象
So to say that my expectations have been exceeded is a sight understatement.

429
0:56:33,040 --> 0:56:34,840
这是我在加拉帕戈斯群岛度过的
This is been one of the most remarkable times

430
0:56:34,840 --> 0:56:36,440
最让人印象深刻的日子之一
I've ever had here in the Galapagos.

431
0:56:47,200 --> 0:56:48,560
下一次
Next time...

432
0:56:49,000 --> 0:56:53,600
我们将环游世界 来记录人类如今面临的首要海洋问题
We travel the world to uncover the biggest issues facing the ocean...

433
0:56:56,720 --> 0:56:58,480
我们将拜访一群
meet the passionate people

434
0:56:58,560 --> 0:57:01,240
将毕生奉献给保护海洋的人
who've devoted their lives to protecting it

435
0:57:02,640 --> 0:57:07,400
我们也将探索这个蓝色星球的未来
and discover what the future holds for our blue planet.

436
